<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">The Math Behind the Calculator</h2>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    You don't need to memorize these formulas, but understanding them helps you trust the results.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">The Pythagorean Theorem</h3>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    This formula dates back over 2,500 years and remains the foundation of right triangle geometry: <span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">a² + b² = c²</span>.
  </p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Take both legs, square each value, and add them together. This gives you the hypotenuse squared. To find the hypotenuse, take the square root of that sum. To find a missing leg, take the square root of the hypotenuse squared minus the other leg squared.
  </p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Example: if a = 3 and b = 4, then c = √(9 + 16) = √25 = 5. This is the well-known 3-4-5 right triangle, used by builders for centuries to verify square corners.
  </p>

  <img src="/images/right-triangle-pythagorean-theorem.webp" alt="Pythagorean theorem diagram showing a right triangle with sides a, b, c and the formula a squared plus b squared equals c squared" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-slate-200 my-6" loading="lazy" width="1200" height="400" />
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Using Sine, Cosine, and Tangent</h3>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    When only one side and one angle are known, trigonometric ratios — sine, cosine, and tangent — can be used to find the remaining values.
  </p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    These relationships are commonly remembered using the mnemonic <a href="https://www.mathsisfun.com/sine-cosine-tangent.html" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium">SOH CAH TOA</a>: sine equals the opposite side divided by the hypotenuse, cosine equals the adjacent side divided by the hypotenuse, and tangent equals the opposite side divided by the adjacent side.
  </p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    For example, if the hypotenuse is 10 and angle α is 30°, then leg a = 10 × sin(30°) = 10 × 0.5 = 5.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Finding Angles Using Inverse Trigonometric Functions</h3>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    If both sides are known but the angles are not, inverse trigonometric functions — arcsin and arctan — can be used to calculate them.
  </p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Take the arcsin of the opposite side divided by the hypotenuse, or the arctan of the opposite side divided by the adjacent side. The remaining angle is then 90° minus the calculated angle, since the two non-right angles in a right triangle always sum to 90°.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Calculating Area, Perimeter, and Altitude of a Right Triangle</h3>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Once all three sides are known, the remaining values are simple to calculate.
  </p>

  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4">
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Area</span> = (leg a × leg b) ÷ 2</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Perimeter</span> = leg a + leg b + hypotenuse</li>
    <li><span class="font-semibold text-slate-800">Altitude</span> = (leg a × leg b) ÷ hypotenuse — the perpendicular height from the right angle to the hypotenuse</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Common Right Triangle Calculations</h2>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Below are the most common scenarios this calculator handles, along with worked examples for each.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Finding the Hypotenuse When Both Legs Are Known</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Given two legs — for example, leg a = 5 and leg b = 12 — the calculator finds the hypotenuse using c = √(a² + b²).
  </p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Example: a wheelchair ramp has a height of 3 feet and a ground distance of 4 feet. The ramp length is √(9 + 16) = √25 = 5 feet.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Finding a Missing Side When the Hypotenuse and One Leg Are Known</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Given the hypotenuse and one leg, the calculator finds the remaining leg using a = √(c² − b²).
  </p>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Example: a 13-foot ladder is positioned 5 feet from a wall. The height it reaches is √(169 − 25) = √144 = 12 feet.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Finding the Perimeter of a Right Triangle</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    The perimeter is simply the sum of all three sides. A 3-4-5 triangle has a perimeter of 12 — useful for estimating material needed around the edges of a project.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Finding Any Side of a Right Triangle</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    If two sides are known, use the Pythagorean theorem. If one side and one angle are known, use sine, cosine, or tangent.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Finding the Angles of a Right Triangle</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    The calculator uses arctan or arcsin depending on the known values. For example, if a = 3 and b = 4, then α ≈ 36.87° and β ≈ 53.13°.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Finding the Area of a Right Triangle</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    The area is calculated by multiplying the two legs and dividing by 2. Legs of 6 and 8 give an area of 24.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Finding the Altitude of a Right Triangle</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    The altitude is found by multiplying the legs and dividing by the hypotenuse. For a 3-4-5 triangle, the altitude is 12 ÷ 5 = 2.4.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">Special Right Triangles the Calculator Detects</h2>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    When your triangle matches a known special right triangle pattern, the calculator automatically identifies it.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">The 45-45-90 Triangle</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Both legs are equal in length, with angles of 45°, 45°, and 90°. The sides are always in the ratio 1 : 1 : √2. For example, if each leg is 1, the hypotenuse is approximately 1.414. This triangle appears frequently in tile work, square corners, and computer graphics.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">The 30-60-90 Triangle</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Angles of 30°, 60°, and 90°, with sides in the ratio 1 : √3 : 2. The shortest leg is opposite the 30° angle. For example, if the short leg is 5, the long leg is approximately 8.66 and the hypotenuse is 10. This triangle is common in roof framing, hexagonal structures, and navigation.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-800 mt-6 mb-2">Pythagorean Triples</h3>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    <a href="https://www.khanacademy.org/test-prep/v2-sat-math/x0fcc98a58ba3bea7:geometry-and-trigonometry-easier/x0fcc98a58ba3bea7:right-triangle-trigonometry-easier/a/v2-sat-lesson-right-triangle-trigonometry" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium">Pythagorean triples</a> are sets of whole numbers that satisfy a² + b² = c² exactly. The most common is 3-4-5, with others including 5-12-13, 7-24-25, 8-15-17, and 9-40-41. These values appear frequently in textbooks and exams.
  </p>

